Here is what went wrong 

    var query = &quot;\&quot;info.name\&quot;: \&quot;ABC\&quot;&quot;;
    { $match: &quot;&quot;info.name&quot;: &quot;ABC&quot;&quot; } // This is single string

Here in this query, we get single string that&#39;s why not result filter 
But when you are using explicitly passing like this ` &quot;info.name&quot;: &quot;ABC&quot; ` it work

For data

    { 
      _id: ObjectId(XXXXXXXXXX),
      info: { name: &quot;ABC&quot; }
    }

You can use this aggregate query  

    // Create object and use this into [$match][1] stage
       const data = { &quot;info.name&quot;: &quot;ABC&quot; };
    // Use this object in match stag
             .aggregate([{ $match: data}])

if you have array of object then you need to use [$elemMatch][2]

 For data

     {  
         _id: ObjectId(XXXXXXXXXX)
         info: [{ name: &quot;ABC&quot; }, { name: &quot;DEF&quot; } ]
    }
    // use elemMatch if array of object
         .aggregate([{ $match:  { info: { $elemMatch:{ name:  &quot;ABC&quot; }}}}])

 [1]: https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/reference/operator/aggregation/match/
[2]:  https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/reference/operator/query/elemMatch/

It works when you pass a query object that is like;

    var query = {
        &quot;info.name&quot;: &quot;ABC&quot;
    }

and passed into the aggregation pipe like so;

    { $match: query }

You can see its details on [MongoDB Node.js Driver Tutorials][1]


----------

You cannot use a JSON object to query nested fields, like;

    var query = {
        info: {
            name: &quot;ABC&quot;
        }
    }

check [here](https://mongoplayground.net/p/YNXObr1KefF)

unless `info` contains only `name` field, then it can be used in such a manner. But again you have to pass with `{ $match: query }`, like [here](https://mongoplayground.net/p/6hgfGuAuJCP)


  [1]: http://mongodb.github.io/node-mongodb-native/3.2/tutorials/aggregation/

As [MongoDB documentation][1] says:

&gt; To specify a query condition on fields in an embedded/nested document, use dot notation.

The actual problem is that you have your object property name as a variable in your JS code. Please, check [how to add a property to a JavaScript object using a variable as the name][2].

Here is how you can do it:


    var propertyName = &quot;info.name&quot;
    var query = {}
    query[propertyName] = &quot;ABC&quot;
    ...

  [1]: https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/tutorial/query-embedded-documents/#query-on-nested-field
  [2]: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/695050/add-a-property-to-a-javascript-object-using-a-variable-as-the-name

